#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:20
msgid ""
"The shell is the command interpreter of Linux.  It is a binary that is not "
"part of the kernel, but forms an additional layer, hence its name \"shell\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:22
msgid ""
"It parses the commands entered by the user and then executes them by the "
"system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:25
msgid ""
"There are several shells, all of which share some common features.  The user "
"is free to use the one that suits him/her best. Some examples are:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:30
msgid "the **Bourne-Again shell** (`bash`),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:30
msgid "the **Korn shell** (`ksh`),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:30
msgid "the **C shell** (`csh`),"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:30
msgid "etc."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:33
msgid ""
"`bash` is present by default in most (all) Linux distributions.  It is "
"characterized by its practical and user-friendly features."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:35
msgid ""
"The shell is also a **basic programming language** which, thanks to some "
"dedicated commands, allows:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:39
msgid "the use of **variables**,"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:39
msgid "**conditional execution** of commands,"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:39
msgid "the **repetition** of commands."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:41
msgid ""
"Shell scripts have the advantage that they can be created **quickly** and "
"**reliably**, without **compiling** or installing additional commands. A "
"shell script is just a text file without any embellishments (bold, italics, "
"etc.)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:43
msgid "!!! NOTE"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:45
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Although the shell is a \"basic\" programming language, it is still very powerful and sometimes faster than badly compiled code.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:49
msgid ""
"To write a shell script, you just have to put all the necessary commands in "
"a single text file.  By making this file executable the shell reads it "
"sequentially, and executes the commands in it one by one.  It is also "
"possible to execute it by passing the name of the script as an argument to "
"the bash binary."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:53
msgid ""
"When the shell encounters an error, it displays a message to identify the "
"problem but continues to execute the script.  But there are mechanisms to "
"stop the execution of a script when an error occurs.  Command-specific "
"errors are also displayed on the screen or inside files."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:55
msgid "What is a good script? It is:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:59
msgid "**reliable**: its operation is flawless even in case of misuse;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:59
msgid ""
"**commented**: its code is annotated to facilitate the rereading and future "
"evolution;"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:59
msgid ""
"**readable**: the code is indented appropriately, the commands are spaced "
"out, ..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/books/learning_bash/00-toc.md:59
msgid ""
"**portable**: the code runs on any Linux system, dependency management, "
"rights management, etc."
msgstr ""
